Come for the Optimism, stay for the in-depth analyses of tech companies and=
 trends:
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday! We=E2=80=99re launching a new weekly newsletter today: Weekly=
 Dose of Optimism.=20
Not Boring=E2=80=99s mission is to make the world more optimistic.
A few weeks ago, I wrote Optimism [https://substack.com/redirect/86c2e3be-1=
eb2-40dc-b9a6-3d3f2baed387?u=3D16283549] to make the case that there=E2=80=
=99s a lot to be optimistic about, and that it=E2=80=99s important to be op=
timistic in order to progress. At the end of that essay, I asked whether yo=
u would want to receive a weekly roundup of optimistic stories, and receive=
d a lot of positive responses. Last Friday, I tweeted the first Weekly Dose=
:
I said if the tweet got over 100 likes, I=E2=80=99d turn this into a newsle=
tter. Here we are.=20
The idea here is simple: ten articles, essays, companies, ideas, podcasts, =
or videos I came across that week that made me more optimistic about the fu=
ture.=20
These aren=E2=80=99t likely to be feel good or human interest stories, alth=
ough a few might slip in. The point isn=E2=80=99t, =E2=80=9CThings are brut=
al, here=E2=80=99s a cat video to cheer you up.=E2=80=9D This isn=E2=80=99t=
 about market or financial optimism, either. We won=E2=80=99t share article=
s that explain why the price of some stock or token is going to go up next =
week.=20
We=E2=80=99re going for a combination of the JFK =E2=80=9CWe choose to go t=
o the Moon, not because it is easy but because it is hard=E2=80=9D optimism=
 and the David Deutsch Principle of Optimism: =E2=80=9CAll evils are caused=
 by insufficient knowledge.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re just going to share stories of humans doing cool shit, pushin=
g frontiers, and learning new things. Humans, for the most part, rock.=20
I want this to be collaborative. When you come across examples, drop them h=
ere [https://substack.com/redirect/7aeee176-039c-4643-aae8-62bed8175936?u=
=3D16283549]. I=E2=80=99ll be sure to give you credit for sharing them. And=
 please give us feedback.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
Week 2: July 8, 2022
They will marvel at how vulnerable the repository of all our potential once=
 was; how perilous our infancy; how humble our beginnings; how many rivers =
we had to cross, before we found our way.
h/t to Rahul for sharing on Twitter [https://substack.com/redirect/0642c081=
-f407-4061-8eb9-fe066daf0ba8?u=3D16283549]
(1): He Dropped Out to Become a Poet. Now He=E2=80=99s Won a Fields Medal. =
[https://substack.com/redirect/0affff94-1293-4193-a67a-11b78c228490?u=3D162=
83549]
By: Jordana Cepelwicz in Quanta Magazine
That poetic detour has since proved crucial to his mathematical breakthroug=
hs. His artistry, according to his colleagues, is evident in the way he unc=
overs those just-right objects at the center of his work, and in the way he=
 seeks a deeper significance in everything he does.
Princeton=E2=80=99s June Huh is one of four mathematicians who received the=
 most recent Fields Medal, =E2=80=9Cwhich are given out once every four yea=
rs to some of the most accomplished mathematicians under the age of 40,=E2=
=80=9D including Maryna Viazovska, the second female recipient of the award=
 in its 82 year history.=20
Huh was a self-described mediocre math student in high school, dropped out =
of college to pursue poetry, and didn=E2=80=99t start studying math formall=
y until he was 23. Beautifully, it seems that Huh=E2=80=99s experience with=
 poetry, or the same thing in his brain that drew him to it, landed him amo=
ng the world=E2=80=99s top mathematicians by seeing problems differently th=
an they do.=20
More on all the medalists in The New York Times [https://substack.com/redir=
ect/6529506f-70ec-4ec3-87b2-8c94bedf5eac?u=3D16283549].
(2) Why go to space? [https://substack.com/redirect/517369e6-f929-4428-adeb=
-7f2a65242a77?u=3D16283549]=20
By: Eli Dourado [https://substack.com/redirect/2787819b-fa6a-42d8-91bc-a5a2=
d2635697?u=3D16283549] (our first two-time Weekly Doser, two weeks in!)
The final reason for continued investment in space=E2=80=94and for me, the =
clincher=E2=80=94is the need for a frontier. Human institutions develop rig=
idity and rot over time, and they must be renewed by striking out into new =
terrain and rebuilding. It=E2=80=99s even better if the new outpost of civi=
lization is fraught with peril.
Dourado highlights the benefits of going to space in four areas:
Improving daily life on Earth
Protecting and preserving democracy
Enriching science and research
Satisfying humanity=E2=80=99s need for a frontier
For a deeper dive, I highly recommend Robert Zubrin=E2=80=99s The Case for =
Space [https://substack.com/redirect/497e7e35-d756-4e9a-9d4e-5a03a4e9ae81?u=
=3D16283549].
(3) Webb Telescope Will Look for Signs of Life Way Out There [https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/a412c8a8-d7e4-4fca-8e21-694bb1951f14?u=3D16283549]
By: Carl Zimmer, The New York Times
This month will mark a new chapter in the search for extraterrestrial life,=
 when the most powerful space telescope yet built will start spying on plan=
ets that orbit other stars. Astronomers hope that the James Webb Space Tele=
scope will reveal whether some of those planets harbor atmospheres that mig=
ht support life.
Speaking of space, the Webb Telescope will begin taking pictures as it orbi=
ts around the sun after 25 years=E2=80=99 of work. Webb will be so cold (be=
low 40 Kelvin) that it will be able to see the early universe more than 13.=
5 billion years ago. Astronomers plan to examine the atmospheres around pla=
nets orbiting other stars, something previous telescopes weren=E2=80=99t po=
werful enough to do. They=E2=80=99re looking for signs of atmospheres that =
might be able to support life.=20
While Webb is a step closer to finding extraterrestrial life, if it=E2=80=
=99s out there, it=E2=80=99s also a celebration of the ingenuity of humans =
on this planet. =E2=80=9CWebb is not just the product of a group of people.=
 It=E2=80=99s not the product of some smart astronomers=E2=80=94Webb is tru=
ly the product of our entire world=E2=80=99s capability,=E2=80=9D Keith Par=
rish [https://substack.com/redirect/616a7144-2a61-46ad-8dba-743464b8c7a6?u=
=3D16283549], a leader on the Webb team at NASA=E2=80=99s Goddard Space Fli=
ght Center [https://substack.com/redirect/6e187235-4cb4-418f-b581-09ea46592=
0a5?u=3D16283549] in Maryland, told IEEE [https://substack.com/redirect/778=
f9fc9-4bd5-4d84-8f19-14edebba71c2?u=3D16283549]. =E2=80=9CTaken as a whole,=
 Webb is truly the result of our entire know-how of how to build complex ma=
chines.=E2=80=9D
(4) Ten years on from the Higgs boson, what is next for physics? [https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/1ac9a7de-11a0-49ae-bdc8-7af2a1a522a7?u=3D16283549]
From: The Economist
To the person in the street this may not sound a big deal. To a physicist i=
t is practically an invitation to book a flight to Stockholm. A violation o=
f lepton universality would be a crack in what is called the Standard Model=
, and therefore Nobel prizewinning stuff.
On Tuesday, CERN turned on the Large Hadron Collider (LHC) for the first ti=
me in 3.5 years after taking it offline for upgrades. As this article point=
s out, discoveries from the last run are shaking long-held assumptions in p=
hysics and refining how we understand the world. They also discovered three=
 subatomic particles [https://substack.com/redirect/0bc9de52-0fa6-452a-9264=
-0ebdadc60fe0?u=3D16283549] that are consistent with the Standard Model
In this run, at higher energies than ever before, scientists are looking to=
 better understand mysterious phenomena like dark matter.=20
(5) Demis Hassabis: DeepMind =E2=80=94 Lex Fridman Podcast
If you think of mathematics as the perfect descriptive language for physics=
, AI is perfect the descriptive language of biology because it=E2=80=99s so=
 messy, emergent, dynamic and complex=E2=80=A6
DeepMind [https://substack.com/redirect/340d9646-bdfa-4063-b4d7-388d0944e7f=
1?u=3D16283549] is an Alphabet-owned AI lab =E2=80=9Ccommitted to solving i=
ntelligence, to advance science and benefit humanity.=E2=80=9D DeepMind=E2=
=80=99s AlphaGo beat the world=E2=80=99s best Go players, something AI rese=
archers thought might never be possible given the game=E2=80=99s complexity=
, and its AlphaFold solved protein folding, a decades-old challenge in biol=
ogy. DeepMind open-sourced the model in order to let researchers and drug d=
evelopers build on top of it. Now, it=E2=80=99s turning its attention to pr=
oblems like recreating a full cell and solving nuclear fusion.
Even before (and even if we never get to) AGI, AI=E2=80=99s impact is going=
 to be more profound and world-changing than most people anticipate (or eve=
n think about).
(6): 24 charts that show we=E2=80=99re (mostly) living better than our pare=
nts [https://substack.com/redirect/0eea6d92-bc60-4143-a4d2-6728c436c0ab?u=
=3D16283549]
By: Timothy B. Lee [https://substack.com/redirect/397bbb7d-6604-4524-9471-1=
e54d8d855fe?u=3D16283549] at Full Stack Economics
Not every facet of our economic life is improving, of course. College tuiti=
on has risen a lot, and so have rents in some big metro areas. But even in =
problem sectors like health care, housing, and education, the situation isn=
=E2=80=99t as grim as pessimists claim. And there are many other areas of e=
conomic life where we are unambiguously better off than our parents.
Lee presents 24 charts that show that, despite the headlines, we=E2=80=99re=
 better off than our parents in a lot of ways. We=E2=80=99re eating more fr=
uits and veggies, cars are cheaper, more powerful, and safer, policy has he=
lped boost incomes of the lowest-income people, we have more household appl=
iances, rents are actually growing less slowly than income in major cities,=
 we=E2=80=99re less vulnerable to heart disease, and we=E2=80=99re able to =
produce more GDP with less carbon.=20
(7): The Future Will Have to Wait [https://substack.com/redirect/dc64be6f-3=
703-4f54-b5d0-746ec72df771?u=3D16283549]
By: Michael Chabon, Submitted by: Ben Springwater [https://substack.com/red=
irect/1ac06e96-6997-436d-b985-3ca66f7096f6?u=3D16283549]
If you have children, I don=E2=80=99t see how you can fail to do everything=
 in your power to ensure that you win your bet, and that they, and their gr=
andchildren, and their grandchildren=E2=80=99s grandchildren, will inherit =
a world whose perfection can never be accomplished by creatures whose imagi=
nation for perfecting it is limitless and free.
This is an oldie (2006) but a goodie that Ben Springwater shared with me th=
is week.=20
(8): Wild mammals are making a comeback in Europe thanks to conservation ef=
forts [https://substack.com/redirect/6264d20a-2d5d-4bc7-83ae-7bc353b83389?u=
=3D16283549]
High agricultural productivity is key to protecting wildlife. We need to pr=
oduce more from less so that we can leave wild spaces for the world=E2=80=
=99s animals to flourish.=C2=A0
Europeans are hunting wild mammals less and using less land for agriculture=
, returning the land to its original inhabitants.=20
(9) The Network State and How to Start a New Country
By: Balaji Srinivasan [https://substack.com/redirect/87b596db-dfd7-4ffe-900=
3-182e57fd130f?u=3D16283549] & Tim Ferriss [https://substack.com/redirect/0=
1e50629-950f-432f-9923-564f506dbbc7?u=3D16283549]
Not everything can endure=E2=80=A6 and we need to think about positive new =
models of the future that do not involve condemning the past=E2=80=A6 Maybe=
 I=E2=80=99m completely wrong
I wasn=E2=80=99t sure whether or not to include this one in the =E2=80=9Cop=
timism=E2=80=9D category =E2=80=94 certainly, the near future that Balaji d=
escribes isn=E2=80=99t rainbows and butterflies. But I went with it, becaus=
e Balaji paints a compelling picture of new forms of governance and human o=
rganization born from the internet. If optimism is the belief that we will =
continue to accumulate knowledge to solve problems, more experiments on and=
 evolution in the ways we organize fits the bill.=20
(10): Surely You=E2=80=99re Joking, Mr. Feynman! [https://substack.com/redi=
rect/a1e8db81-bc73-4d98-ac36-8a9f83723061?u=3D16283549]
By: Richard Feynman
The world is full of this kind of dumb smart-alec who doesn=E2=80=99t under=
stand anything.
A couple of years ago, my friend Lauralynn recommended physicist Richard Fe=
ynman=E2=80=99s autobiography to me. I think she said it was her favorite b=
ook. I just got around to reading it, and even though I=E2=80=99m not quite=
 halfway done yet, I feel good recommending it to you.=20
Feynman=E2=80=99s curiosity and mischievousness jump off the page, and his =
approach to figuring things out make me want to understand things more deep=
ly. As he wrote to end a chapter, =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t know what=E2=80=
=99s the matter with people: they don=E2=80=99t learn by understanding; the=
y learn by some other way=E2=80=94by rote, or something. Their knowledge is=
 so fragile!=E2=80=9D=20
Pulling this whole thing together, Feynman wrote:=20
So I got a great reputation for doing integrals, only because my box of too=
ls was different from everybody else=E2=80=99s, and they had tried all thei=
r tools on it before giving the problem to me.
=E2=80=A6 which sounds an awful lot like June Huh.=20
Not everything is great. The war in Ukraine rages on. The political situati=
on in the UK is a mess. Layoffs are still widespread. As one Twitter user p=
ointed out [https://substack.com/redirect/27aec8a6-5323-4013-a096-ed90b73a2=
e5e?u=3D16283549], the US =E2=80=9Cis told what laws are by an unelected co=
uncil of wizards that try to guess what the ghost of thomas jefferson reall=
y meant.=E2=80=9D =20
And tragically, former Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe was assassinated =
this morning [https://substack.com/redirect/eaf561e5-a2bc-4ce2-86fe-732060f=
bce49?u=3D16283549]. Things aren=E2=80=99t perfect, and there=E2=80=99s a l=
ot of work to be done.
I hope this newsletter makes you a little more optimistic heading into the =
weekend. It=E2=80=99s very much a work-in-progress =E2=80=94 please send fe=
edback (including whether or not you think we should keep sending it!), and=
 help us out by submitting the things you come across that make you most op=
timistic here [https://substack.com/redirect/7aeee176-039c-4643-aae8-62bed8=
175936?u=3D16283549].
Have a great weekend!=20
Packy

